WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.200
We're living in a world right now where we have more data than we know what to do with

00:00:07.200 --> 00:00:08.440
almost, right?

00:00:08.440 --> 00:00:12.600
And so then we turn that corner to what are those insights?

00:00:12.600 --> 00:00:15.000
What are those specific tools?

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:18.240
What's that specific leverage that we can get to our customers?

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:22.639
And that's really, I think, what we wake up every day and try to put that thinking cap

00:00:22.639 --> 00:00:27.240
on and empathize with the end golfer, try to solve problems for them.

00:00:27.240 --> 00:00:31.080
They might not even know they have.

00:00:31.080 --> 00:00:33.240
There's been an explosion of data.

00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:40.639
So data on how different golf balls fly, data on how golfers move around the course.

00:00:40.639 --> 00:00:47.520
And then layer on top of that, intelligent analytics on what does that data mean?

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:53.919
And so we now need to figure out how to take that data, take those measurements, analyze

00:00:53.919 --> 00:00:59.840
it and ultimately extract insights to help people play better golf, enjoy the game more.

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:07.000
And that requires tools and structures to help us not only process and analyze that

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:12.360
data, but then also deliver it to the end user and help the customer understand and

00:01:12.360 --> 00:01:16.080
leverage those insights that we're getting from these new measurements and new technologies.

00:01:16.080 --> 00:01:20.040
It's amazing what smart people can accomplish with good tools.

00:01:20.040 --> 00:01:25.360
But then being able to take that and quickly turn it into a production grade, commercially

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:29.699
viable web app and get that out to the public was, that was a big win.

00:01:29.699 --> 00:01:34.480
And since then, we've taken that momentum and repeated it several more times.

00:01:34.480 --> 00:01:39.559
I think we're just at the very beginning of being able to bring this collection of tools

00:01:39.559 --> 00:01:41.400
to the everyday golfer.

00:01:41.400 --> 00:01:52.279
So I was introduced to Ping through a colleague who is a designer here.

00:01:52.279 --> 00:01:55.559
And I got in, started working part-time in the manufacturing engineering group.

00:01:55.559 --> 00:01:57.160
And I just love the culture.

00:01:57.160 --> 00:01:58.279
I love solving problems.

00:01:58.279 --> 00:02:02.559
I never envisioned that I would use my engineering degree to even get into golf design.

00:02:02.559 --> 00:02:06.800
So it's been a very fun journey because I've been able to invest time in my game, follow

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:11.520
my passion, get better at golf, join the PGA of America, and that's opened up some

00:02:11.520 --> 00:02:14.880
doors to play competitive tournament golf.

00:02:14.880 --> 00:02:17.240
But when that door opened to get in here, I loved it.

00:02:17.240 --> 00:02:18.240
I loved the culture.

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:25.600
I loved learning about all the unknowns, all the golf physics that was there and the curiosity.

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:26.600
I was an R&D engineer.

00:02:26.600 --> 00:02:28.119
He was a designer.

00:02:28.119 --> 00:02:32.000
He always has just been really consumed with what the customer needs.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:33.720
How do I help somebody play the game more?

00:02:33.720 --> 00:02:38.839
And I was more on the research side trying to help answer the questions that he was posing.

00:02:38.839 --> 00:02:44.839
I think that culture of being so curious about how things work and then being able to kind

00:02:44.839 --> 00:02:50.679
of take ownership to try to solve a problem and then ultimately turn it into a solution

00:02:50.679 --> 00:02:53.720
for the customer, right?

00:02:53.720 --> 00:02:54.880
And I love that.

00:02:54.880 --> 00:03:00.039
As I started working here at Ping, I started playing golf more and more and that became

00:03:00.520 --> 00:03:05.720
more of a passion for me even outside of my time here on campus doing the engineering

00:03:05.720 --> 00:03:06.720
things.

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:13.399
And it's really helped me understand the elements of the game that are a challenge, the pain

00:03:13.399 --> 00:03:15.600
of a player trying to get better.

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:20.539
And it's really helped me understand how to ask the right research questions and tackle

00:03:20.539 --> 00:03:23.399
the right areas to help make golf equipment better.

00:03:23.399 --> 00:03:27.279
A lot of new people got introduced to golf during the past few years.

00:03:27.279 --> 00:03:33.039
And so there's kind of a younger generation, a network of golfers that previously weren't

00:03:33.039 --> 00:03:34.960
introduced to the game are out there.

00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:39.880
And so we've tried to just really, both from a product standpoint, from a custom-fitting

00:03:39.880 --> 00:03:42.559
standpoint, try to continue that momentum.

00:03:50.320 --> 00:03:55.039
Ping was founded by a frustrated engineer, Karsten Solheim.

00:03:55.039 --> 00:04:00.199
He founded the company because he looked at how equipment was designed and said, hey,

00:04:00.199 --> 00:04:06.479
I could bring my engineering background and make the game way easier through some fundamental

00:04:06.479 --> 00:04:07.759
physics principles.

00:04:07.759 --> 00:04:12.000
And it's still kind of in the DNA of Ping in what we do.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:18.160
Every company develops little centers of excellence, groups of one or two folks who try to solve

00:04:18.160 --> 00:04:22.100
a problem the best way they can or the best way they know how.

00:04:22.380 --> 00:04:26.859
One of those that had developed at Ping that I learned about was a group in engineering

00:04:26.859 --> 00:04:33.540
that were using the R programming language to help visualize and share insights and information

00:04:33.540 --> 00:04:37.540
about golf data and how we do business.

00:04:37.540 --> 00:04:43.619
Initially, we started looking at Shiny apps to help just visualize and quickly draw insights

00:04:43.619 --> 00:04:49.579
from data that we acquired on a range here, through player testing, from a motion capture

00:04:49.579 --> 00:04:50.579
system.

00:04:50.579 --> 00:04:57.140
Shiny apps at Ping really are where the first value from R came out.

00:04:57.140 --> 00:05:01.380
That's Dr. Hendrickson and Marty and their teams who are the clever folks behind those.

00:05:01.380 --> 00:05:07.700
A lot of these physics-based and data-driven models that we were developing, we were developing

00:05:07.700 --> 00:05:15.700
them using PositRStudio, then using the Shiny framework, developing these dashboards for

00:05:15.700 --> 00:05:20.179
our engineers to then use these models and use the data we get from player testing and

00:05:20.179 --> 00:05:24.619
motion capture testing to design equipment.

00:05:24.619 --> 00:05:27.940
We went to Doug and we're like, hey, we have these models.

00:05:27.940 --> 00:05:33.579
We're using this Shiny framework to develop these Shiny dashboards and apps to beta test

00:05:33.579 --> 00:05:38.339
some different ideas we have for tools that would help both engineers as well as the end

00:05:38.339 --> 00:05:39.339
consumer.

00:05:39.339 --> 00:05:43.820
Dr. Hendrickson and his team had identified R as something they wanted to work on and

00:05:43.820 --> 00:05:48.579
something they wanted to do, and they had built a handful of Shiny applications.

00:05:48.619 --> 00:05:52.820
But they did it without the support of IT and without the support of the larger corporate

00:05:52.820 --> 00:05:55.459
digital strategy, because they had to.

00:05:55.459 --> 00:05:56.459
They were solving a problem.

00:05:56.459 --> 00:05:58.100
They were innovating.

00:05:58.100 --> 00:06:03.299
So I was glad to be able to come in and say, that's fantastic, but that doesn't scale.

00:06:03.299 --> 00:06:05.500
Let's try some other techniques.

00:06:05.500 --> 00:06:12.179
And that's where PositConnect came in as not only providing us the ability to publish these

00:06:12.179 --> 00:06:18.940
tools that we're developing, but also host APIs and help us move toward consumer-facing

00:06:18.940 --> 00:06:25.220
applications where we can then build out a front end and then hook that into these APIs

00:06:25.220 --> 00:06:26.459
in PositConnect.

00:06:26.459 --> 00:06:30.820
The big proof of value came the first time that I convinced them to, instead of creating

00:06:30.820 --> 00:06:33.899
a Shiny app, create a Plumber API.

00:06:33.899 --> 00:06:39.140
And then can I share that Plumber API with a team within Ping who can build a web interface

00:06:39.140 --> 00:06:41.619
around it and publish that to the public?

00:06:42.100 --> 00:06:45.279
That really was the, like, okay, this is going to work.

00:06:45.279 --> 00:06:50.700
Instead of rebuilding all of our algorithms and fundamental modeling, we're able to use

00:06:50.700 --> 00:06:58.019
APIs that drive that front end that our customers experience without having to rebuild our prototype.

00:06:58.019 --> 00:07:00.859
We just built our front end right on top of it.

00:07:00.859 --> 00:07:06.660
PositConnect gives a tool set to program real JSON-based APIs.

00:07:06.660 --> 00:07:07.660
That's fundamental.

00:07:07.700 --> 00:07:12.220
If you can't do that, you're going to have a really hard time working with any other system.

00:07:12.220 --> 00:07:16.779
How it works is that we take those models and then we're able to create in that logic

00:07:16.779 --> 00:07:23.899
and develop some APIs, and through the Plumber framework and through Connect, host those

00:07:23.899 --> 00:07:29.899
and then provide this foundation for other tools to be developed.

00:07:29.899 --> 00:07:36.179
Shiny and PositConnect give us that ability to, in a careful way, in a protected way with

00:07:36.179 --> 00:07:42.500
user access controls and a reliable deployment process, it gives us that ability to have

00:07:42.500 --> 00:07:47.980
their projects be shared around the company in a controlled, safe, responsible way.

00:07:47.980 --> 00:07:53.420
What started with me kind of playing with it and prototyping quickly evolved into a

00:07:53.420 --> 00:07:59.140
number of engineers wanting to get their hands dirty, make their own dashboards, do their

00:07:59.140 --> 00:08:01.940
own data analysis, and it exploded really quick.

00:08:01.940 --> 00:08:08.899
To me, what PositConnect did for us was really brought that likelihood of getting value from

00:08:08.899 --> 00:08:14.899
the investment and the time and the expertise in data science that shortened that lifecycle

00:08:14.899 --> 00:08:17.779
a lot to, can we get this out?

00:08:17.779 --> 00:08:23.100
Can we build a consumer-facing product that has commercial value quickly and cost-efficiently

00:08:23.100 --> 00:08:25.179
and try to see if it's worth it?

00:08:25.179 --> 00:08:28.899
And I'm happy to say that the solution we've got in place right now lets us experiment

00:08:28.899 --> 00:08:29.899
really, really fast.

00:08:30.459 --> 00:08:36.659
It's a lot of fun to be able to kind of help build this ecosystem around data, not only

00:08:36.659 --> 00:08:41.299
data when you're hitting balls on a driving range or when you're testing clubs or hitting

00:08:41.299 --> 00:08:46.979
in a simulator bay, but more importantly, what is your data on the golf course while

00:08:46.979 --> 00:08:52.580
you're playing golf, and how can you tie those things together and make better product decisions,

00:08:52.580 --> 00:08:57.539
custom-fitting decisions, where should you be practicing your game, where are you going

00:08:57.539 --> 00:09:01.219
to get the most leverage from your practice and your training, and it's still early for

00:09:01.219 --> 00:09:05.619
us to make those tools available to a lot of golfers at scale.

00:09:05.619 --> 00:09:12.340
Looking at Posit, and specifically PositConnect, was not a short-term solution.

00:09:12.340 --> 00:09:19.580
I saw it as a strategic component of a long-term vision for digital technology at PING, if

00:09:19.580 --> 00:09:22.539
it worked out, which I'm really glad to say it did.

00:09:22.539 --> 00:09:24.820
I don't see that runway ending.

00:09:24.820 --> 00:09:27.219
It's a foundational component to how we continue innovating.

